# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

In the SURPASS-1 trial of patients with type 2 diabetes, tirzepatide demonstrated dose-dependent reductions in HbA1c and body weight.[1] In SURPASS-3, tirzepatide was compared with insulin degludec as an add-on to metformin with or without SGLT2 inhibitors.[2] The SURPASS-4 trial compared tirzepatide versus insulin glargine in patients with type 2 diabetes and increased cardiovascular risk.[3] In Japanese populations, tirzepatide monotherapy was evaluated against dulaglutide in SURPASS J-mono, and as an add-on to oral medication in SURPASS J-combo.[4][5] In Chinese patients with type 2 diabetes on basal insulin, the SURPASS-CN-INS trial assessed tirzepatide added to basal insulin.[6] In a related obesity trial without diabetes, SURMOUNT-4 showed that after a 36-week lead-in with tirzepatide resulting in 20.9% weight reduction, continued treatment led to an additional 5.5% weight loss over 52 weeks, whereas switching to placebo led to 14.0% weight regain.[7]

### Comparative

An adjusted indirect treatment comparison of tirzepatide versus semaglutide 2 mg in patients with type 2 diabetes found that tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg significantly reduced HbA1c versus semaglutide 2 mg, with estimated treatment differences of −0.36% and −0.4%, respectively, and significantly reduced body weight with differences of −3.15 kg and −5.15 kg, respectively.[8] Another indirect comparison in people with obesity or overweight and type 2 diabetes found tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg were associated with significantly greater mean percent weight reductions versus semaglutide 2.4 mg, with mean differences of 2.57% and 4.79%, respectively, and greater HbA1c reductions.[9] In a related obesity trial without diabetes, a direct head-to-head comparison showed a least-squares mean percent change in weight of −20.2% with tirzepatide versus −13.7% with semaglutide.[10] For cardiovascular outcomes in patients with diabetes and cardiovascular disease, tirzepatide was compared with dulaglutide, where a 6-component cardiorenal end point occurred in 23.7% of tirzepatide-treated patients versus 27.4% of dulaglutide-treated patients.[11] One systematic review and meta-analysis of direct comparative studies concluded tirzepatide was significantly superior to semaglutide in achieving weight reduction, with a pooled standardized mean difference of 0.75.[12]

### Safety

In randomized controlled trials, the overall safety profile of tirzepatide is similar to that of GLP-1 receptor agonists, primarily characterized by gastrointestinal adverse events.[13] A systematic review of RCTs found the incidences of nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea were higher than with placebo but consistent with GLP-1 receptor agonists.[13] Regarding hypoglycemia, one systematic review reported tirzepatide 15 mg was associated with more hypoglycemia than GLP-1 receptor agonists (pooled RR=3.83, 95% CI 1.19–12.30) in a pooled analysis of trials.[13] A separate network meta-analysis in patients with obesity or overweight found no significant difference in hypoglycemia events between tirzepatide and GLP-1 receptor agonists but noted tirzepatide showed a higher severe hypoglycemia risk (<54 mg/dL).[14] The FAERS analysis reported tirzepatide was associated with a similar risk of diabetic retinopathy and medullary thyroid cancer versus SGLT-2 inhibitors.[15] Despite a black box warning for thyroid C-cell tumors, one retrospective cohort study found patients treated with tirzepatide had a significantly lower incidence of malignant thyroid cancer compared to controls (Relative Risk 0.348, p < 0.001).[16]

### Dose Response

Meta-analyses of randomized controlled trials demonstrate a dose-dependent relationship for tirzepatide's effects on HbA1c and body weight in type 2 diabetes.[17] Another meta-analysis confirmed these trends, finding HbA1c reductions of 0.20% with 10 mg and 0.30% with 15 mg versus 5 mg, and weight reductions of 2.64 kg and 4.26 kg, respectively.[18] A more recent network meta-analysis also found significant reductions in HbA1c with tirzepatide 10 mg (MD: -0.19) and 15 mg (MD: -0.32) versus the 5 mg dose, alongside weight reductions of 1.96 kg and 3.31 kg, respectively.[19] Regarding the time to achieve clinical thresholds, a pre-planned exploratory analysis of the SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 trials found the median time to first achieve a body weight loss of ≥5% was faster with tirzepatide 5 mg (16.0 weeks) and with the 10 and 15 mg doses (12.4 weeks) than with the active comparator semaglutide 1 mg (24.0 weeks).[20] The same analysis reported the median time to achieve HbA1c <7.0% was 8.1 weeks for each tirzepatide dose.[20] In terms of safety, meta-analyses indicate the risk of total adverse events and gastrointestinal adverse events is higher with the 10 mg and 15 mg doses compared to the 5 mg dose.[17][18] One review concluded that within the 5–15 mg range, the effect on lowering glycemia and reducing weight is dose-dependent, with the 15 mg dose achieving the best efficacy, but the 5 mg dose offers a more favorable safety profile.[17]

### Population Subgroups

In older patients with type 2 diabetes and diminished β-cell function, a case report suggests tirzepatide may help control postprandial hyperglycemia but may not replace basal insulin for fasting control, requiring monitoring for sarcopenia.[21] In a prespecified analysis of the SUMMIT trial in patients with heart failure with preserved ejection fraction and obesity, tirzepatide's effect on cardiovascular outcomes was consistent regardless of diabetes status, with a hazard ratio of 0.64 (95% CI: 0.35-1.15) for the composite of cardiovascular death or worsening heart failure in patients with type 2 diabetes and 0.61 (95% CI: 0.33-1.10) in those without diabetes (Pinteraction = 0.95).[22] However, weight loss with tirzepatide was less pronounced in patients with type 2 diabetes (10.4% [95% CI: 8.7%-12.2%]) compared to those without diabetes (12.9% [95% CI: 11.2%-14.6%]) (Pinteraction = 0.04).[22] Weight loss was significantly greater in patients with higher baseline body weight (≥75 kg) across all tirzepatide doses.[23] A separate post-hoc analysis of SURPASS trials indicated that tirzepatide was effective in reducing HbA1c and body weight in patients with glutamic acid decarboxylase autoantibodies (GADA-positive), though the HbA1c reduction was slightly less compared to GADA-negative patients (estimated treatment difference 0.21% [95% CI: 0.03, 0.39]; p=0.024).[24]

### Limitations

Limitations: The corpus has significant gaps in its tier distribution, with only 18% of sources being T1 primary studies and a substantial 28% classified as T4 preprints. The pipeline detected 12 high-severity contradictions, primarily concerning tirzepatide's effect on body weight, where sources disagree dramatically on the magnitude of the reported effect across different dosages. The evidence horizon spans from 2010 to the present, but the high volume of lower-tier evidence and preprints indicates a reliance on less mature research.

