outputs/full_scale_v7/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm\report.md:17:Meta-analyses of randomized controlled trials demonstrate a dose-dependent relationship for tirzepatide's effects on HbA1c and body weight in type 2 diabetes.[17] Another meta-analysis confirmed these trends, finding HbA1c reductions of 0.20% with 10 mg and 0.30% with 15 mg versus 5 mg, and weight reductions of 2.64 kg and 4.26 kg, respectively.[18] A more recent network meta-analysis also found significant reductions in HbA1c with tirzepatide 10 mg (MD: -0.19) and 15 mg (MD: -0.32) versus the 5 mg dose, alongside weight reductions of 1.96 kg and 3.31 kg, respectively.[19] Regarding the time to achieve clinical thresholds, a pre-planned exploratory analysis of the SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 trials found the median time to first achieve a body weight loss of ≥5% was faster with tirzepatide 5 mg (16.0 weeks) and with the 10 and 15 mg doses (12.4 weeks) than with the active comparator semaglutide 1 mg (24.0 weeks).[20] The same analysis reported the median time to achieve HbA1c <7.0% was 8.1 weeks for each tirzepatide dose.[20] In terms of safety, meta-analyses indicate the risk of total adverse events and gastrointestinal adverse events is higher with the 10 mg and 15 mg doses compared to the 5 mg dose.[17][18] One review concluded that within the 5–15 mg range, the effect on lowering glycemia and reducing weight is dose-dependent, with the 15 mg dose achieving the best efficacy, but the 5 mg dose offers a more favorable safety profile.[17]
