# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

Tirzepatide demonstrated significant, dose-dependent improvements in both glycemic control and body weight across the SURPASS clinical trials in adults with type 2 diabetes.[1] The A1C reduction from baseline to the primary end point ranged from −1.87% with tirzepatide 5 mg in SURPASS-1 to −2.59% with tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg in SURPASS-5.[1] In SURPASS-1, the highest dose (15 mg) reduced A1C by 2.07% from baseline and 52% of participants achieved normoglycemia (A1c <5.7%).[1][2] The proportion of participants achieving an A1C value <7.0% with tirzepatide across the trials ranged from 81 to 97%.[1] For weight loss, body weight reductions from baseline at the primary end point ranged from −6.2 kg (−6.6%) with tirzepatide 5 mg when added to insulin glargine (SURPASS-5) to −12.9 kg (−13.9%) with tirzepatide 15 mg when added to metformin with or without an SGLT2 inhibitor (SURPASS-3).[1] Tirzepatide was superior to active comparators, including semaglutide 1 mg and various insulin regimens, in reducing A1C and body weight.[1][3] These effects were consistent across different patient populations and background therapies.[1][4]

### Comparative

In a direct head-to-head trial in patients with obesity without diabetes, tirzepatide demonstrated superior weight loss compared to semaglutide, with a least-squares mean percent change in weight at week 72 of −20.2% versus −13.7%.[5] Participants were also more likely to achieve weight reductions of at least 10%, 15%, 20%, and 25% with tirzepatide.[5] Another phase 3 trial reported a mean percentage change in body weight with tirzepatide of −20.2% compared with −13.7% for semaglutide at 72 weeks.[6] A real-world retrospective cohort study in patients without diabetes also found greater 6-month mean percentage weight reduction with tirzepatide (−11.15%) versus semaglutide (−8.83%).[7] A systematic review and meta-analysis of direct comparative studies concluded tirzepatide was significantly superior to semaglutide in achieving weight reduction, with a greater standardized mean difference for weight loss.[8] For glycemic control in type 2 diabetes, a network meta-analysis found all tirzepatide doses (5, 10, 15 mg) were comparable to semaglutide 2.0 mg and superior to semaglutide 1.0 mg and 0.5 mg in reducing HbA1c.[9] An indirect treatment comparison also concluded tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg were associated with significantly greater mean percent weight reductions versus semaglutide 2.4 mg in people with obesity and type 2 diabetes.[10] Compared to insulin, tirzepatide showed greater efficacy; a meta-analysis found once-weekly tirzepatide significantly decreased HbA1c and body weight compared with daily insulin glargine and degludec, with a lower risk of hypoglycemia.[11] Specifically, in a trial adding therapy to basal insulin, the mean change in HbA1c at week 52 was −2.1% with tirzepatide versus −1.1% with insulin lispro, with less hypoglycemia and more body weight reduction.[12] Another meta-analysis reported all three tirzepatide doses resulted in a significant reduction in HbA1c and a significant decrease in body weight compared with long-acting insulin.[13] Regarding safety, gastrointestinal events were the most common adverse events for both tirzepatide and semaglutide in the head-to-head obesity trial, with one source reporting at least one adverse event in approximately 76.7% of patients on tirzepatide and 79% on semaglutide.[5][6] A network meta-analysis in patients with type 2 diabetes on basal insulin found tirzepatide showed a statistically significant, higher likelihood of experiencing nausea compared with placebo or exenatide, but no significant difference in treatment discontinuation due to adverse events compared to several GLP-1 receptor agonists.[14]

### Safety

Gastrointestinal adverse events are the most commonly reported adverse events with tirzepatide and are dose-dependent, with reported incidences of 39% (95% CI, 35%-43%), 46% (95% CI, 42%-49%), and 49% (95% CI, 38%-60%) for the 5, 10, and 15 mg doses, respectively.[15] Among gastrointestinal events, nausea and diarrhea are the most frequent at any dose.[15] Drug discontinuation due to adverse events was highest with the 15 mg dose at 10%.[15] Regarding hypoglycemia, a meta-analysis found patients treated with tirzepatide had no significantly increased risk compared with placebo overall (OR= 2.05, 95%CI:0.95 to 4.42, p=0.07).[16] Another analysis reported tirzepatide 15mg was associated with more hypoglycemia than GLP-1 receptor agonists (pooled RR=3.83, 95% CI [1.19- 12.30], P=0.02).[17] Conversely, a different study in patients achieving normoglycemia found low rates, with 98.5% not experiencing level 2 or 3 severe hypoglycemia (<54 mg/dL) and 91% not experiencing level 1 hypoglycemia (≤70 mg/dL).[18] Rates of fatal adverse events, severe hypoglycemia, acute pancreatitis, cholelithiasis, and cholecystitis are reported as extremely low (≤ 1%) across all doses.[15] An analysis of FDA adverse event reports suggested an association between tirzepatide and thyroid cancer (reporting odds ratio = 2.09, 95% CI: 1.51–2.89), though this was lower than associations for other GLP-1 receptor agonists.[19]

### Dose Response

The effects of tirzepatide on glycemic and weight outcomes are dose-dependent within the 5 mg to 15 mg range.[20] This analysis also noted that fasting serum glucose showed improvement with the 15 mg dose.[21] One review concluded that within the 5–15 mg dose range, the effect in lowering glycemia and reducing weight is dose-dependent, with the 15 mg dose achieving the best efficacy benefit.[20] A separate meta-analysis confirmed that the 15 mg dose provided the greatest reductions in HbA1c and body weight compared to the 10 mg and 5 mg doses.[22] Regarding safety, gastrointestinal adverse events increased with higher doses, though one analysis reported this increase was without statistical significance.[21] Another analysis found the risk of total adverse events was significantly higher with the 10 mg and 15 mg doses compared to the 5 mg dose.[22]

### Population Subgroups

In a post-hoc analysis of SURPASS-1 to -5, tirzepatide demonstrated significantly greater reductions in HbA1c versus comparators in both prespecified age subgroups (<65 and ≥65 years).[23] Regarding sex, all tirzepatide doses significantly reduced body weight compared to comparators regardless of the sex of study participants across SURPASS-1 to -5.[24] In patients with heart failure with preserved ejection fraction and obesity, tirzepatide produced less weight loss at 52 weeks in those with type 2 diabetes (10.4%) than in those without diabetes (12.9%).[25] However, the effect of tirzepatide on the primary composite of cardiovascular death or worsening heart failure was similar between patients with or without diabetes, with a hazard ratio of 0.64 for patients with diabetes and 0.61 for those without.[25] In a retrospective study of adults with type 1 diabetes and obesity, tirzepatide led to significant weight loss, with a median total body weight loss of 8% at 6 months and a 1% reduction in HbA1c.[26] For individuals with type 2 diabetes who were glutamic acid decarboxylase autoantibody-positive, tirzepatide was effective, achieving HbA1c reductions of -2.11% and body weight reductions of -9.2 kg at 40/42 weeks, though HbA1c reductions were slightly greater in GADA-negative patients.[27] The most frequent adverse events across subgroups were mild-to-moderate and gastrointestinal-related, occurring during dose-escalation.[23][24]

### Limitations

Limitations: The corpus exhibits significant tier-distribution gaps, with only 15% of sources being T1 primary studies and a heavy reliance on T7 sources at 32%. The pipeline detected 11 high-severity contradictions, primarily concerning tirzepatide's effect on body weight, where sources disagree substantially on the magnitude of the reported outcome. The evidence horizon spans from 2010 to the present, which may not capture earlier foundational research.

